Damage from Hurricane Hugo, which stormed through the Carolinas and Caribbean last  week, will reduce several insurers' third-quarter earnings.
American International Group,  which insured property in Puerto Rico, the eastern Caribbean, and the Carolina coast,  expects losses between $35 and $45 million.
St. Paul Cos. said the pretax cost of Hugo  shouldn't exceed $50 million.
Cigna Corp.'s third-quarter per-share earnings could drop  50-65 cents a share.
State Farm's Fire & Casualty unit estimates $400 million in  payments in South Carolina.
Payments in North Carolina and Virginia will bring the total  to $500 million, more than three times its 1983 record payout of $165 million for  Hurricane Alicia. 
